 **nucleophilic addition** (specifically, 1,4-conjugate addition / Michael addition to a vinylic position of an indolium salt).\n\nMore precisely, this is a **1,2-nucleophilic addition** to the C=C bond of the indolium, since the nucleophile adds to the terminal carbon of the exocyclic double bond.\n\nWait, let me reconsider. In the indolium salt, the positive charge is on N. The exocyclic C=C is conjugated with the C=N+ system. The nucleophile (N:10) attacks C:20, which is the terminal carbon of the exocyclic double bond. This is essentially a 1,4-addition (conjugate addition) to the extended C=N+-C=C system, or it could be classified as a 1,2-addition to the C=C.\n\nGiven the SM parameter of 6 and the conditions (MeCN, 293K), this is consistent with an SNAr or nucleophilic addition mechanism.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the reaction center:\n- Bond broken: C:21=C:20 (the exocyclic double bond of the indolium)\n- Bond formed: C:20-N:10 (nucleophilic C-N bond formation)\n- Charge transfer: N+:23 → N:23 (neutralization), N:14 → N+:14 (charge migration)\n\nThe mechanistic class is **nucleophilic addition** (conjugate addition / Michael addition).\n\nFor the reaction center: C:21=C:20 bond cleavage and C:20-N:10 bond formation, with charge migration from N:23 to N:14.\n\nLet me give a compact answer:\n\nMechanistic class: nucleophilic_addition (conjugate addition)\nReaction center: C21=C20 → C21-C20-N10; charge migration N+23→N23, N14→N+14"
